Data Description

This dataset includes two CSV files: players.csv and sessions.csv.

players.csv

There are a total of 196 observations and 7 variables in this dataset. It includes demographics and information about each player who participated in the PLAICraft study. The table below illustrates the datatype and a short description of the variables in the dataset:

Variables Description Datatype
experience The level of experience of the player (beginner, amateur, regular, veteran, pro) character
subscribe Whether the player subscribed to PLAICraft email updates logical
hashedEmail An anonymous email assigned to each player character
played_hours The total number of hours the player has spent in-game double
name An anonymous name the player has chosen for their in-game character character
gender The gender of the player character
age The age of the player integer
Potential Issues:

Data Types: When the data is read into R, a few of the variables are assigned to incorrect data types.

  • Experience should be a factor data type instead of character
  • Gender should be a factor data type instead of character

Missing Data: There are 2 NA values present in the "Age" variable.

sessions.csv

There are a total of 1535 observations and 5 variables in this dataset. It includes information of individual play sessions for each character. The table below illustrates the datatype and a short description of the variables in the dataset:

Variables Description Datatype
hashedEmail An anonymous email assigned to each player character
start_time The date (dd/mm/yyyy) and time (hh:mm) the session began double
end_time The date (dd/mm/yyyy) and time (hh:mm) the session ended character
original_start_time Start time of each session in UNIX format character
original_end_time Start time of each session in UNIX format integer
Potential Issues:

Data Types: start_time and end_time are incorrect data types. They should be expressed as datetime (dttm) data.

Unsuitable Data: original_start_time and original_end_time are in UNIX form, which treats time as a linear scale, ignoring cyclical patterns (e.g., weekdays, seasons). It lacks time zone context and has too few significant figures for precise predictions.

Missing Data: There are 2 missing value inputs in both end_time and original_end_time.

Question to Address:

I would like to address Question 2: Which "kinds" of players are most likely to contribute a large amount of data so that those players can be targeted in recruiting efforts.

I aim to answer my own question: Can age, experience, subscribe and gender predict hours_played in the players.csv dataset?

Response Variable

I will use hours_played as the response variable. "hours_played" refers to the amount of time the player has spent in-game. This variable can help quantify the contribution of a player to the dataset.

Exploratory Variables

I will use age, experience, subscribe and gender as exploratory variables, with age representing a player's age, experience indicating the player's experience level, subscribe indicating whether the player has subscribed to PLAICraft email updates and gender indicating the player's gender.

  • I am interested in how much data gender contributes to the dataset, as I am a female who enjoys video games, and males are stereotypically known to spend more time playing video games compared to females.

  • I also believe there may be patterns in the data based on player experience. A higher experience level could indicate more hours logged on PLAICraft, or it could suggest that experienced players spend less time playing since they have already invested significant time in the game. Meanwhile, beginners may log many hours as they try to improve.

  • Players who have subscribed to PLAICraft email updates may be more engaged with the game, which can lead to more contirbutions to dataset.

  • I am interested in how age influences the number of hours logged and whether younger or older players tend to spend more time playing.

Reading the Files into R

In[3]:
players <- read.csv("players.csv")
sessions <- read.csv("sessions.csv")

Tidying players.csv

mutate(individualId = seq(1, 194)):

  • Adds a new column individualId with a sequence of numbers from 1 to 196.

mutate(experience = as_factor(experience)):

  • Converts the experience column to a factor (categorical variable).

mutate(gender = as_factor(gender)):

  • Converts the gender column to a factor (categorical variable).

filter(!is.na(Age)):

  • removes the missing data.
In[5]:
players <- players |>
    mutate(individualId = seq(1, 196)) |>
    mutate(experience = as_factor(experience),
          gender = as_factor(gender)) |>
    filter(!is.na(Age))

Tidying sessions.csv

mutate(start_time = dmy_hm(start_time), end_time = dmy_hm(end_time)):

  • Converts the start_time and end_time columns from character format to datetime format using the dmy_hm() function (day-month-year hour-minute format).

filter(!is.na(end_time)):

  • Removes rows where the end_time is missing (NA).

filter(!is.na(start_time)):

  • Removes rows where the start_time is missing (NA).

mutate(session_duration_time = as.numeric(difftime(end_time, start_time, units = "hours"))):

  • Creates a new column session_duration_time that calculates the time difference between end_time and start_time in hours.
In[6]:
sessions <- sessions |>
  mutate(start_time = dmy_hm(start_time),
    end_time = dmy_hm(end_time)) |> 
    filter(!is.na(end_time)) |>
    filter(!is.na(start_time))

sessions <- sessions |>
    mutate(session_duration_time = as.numeric(difftime(end_time, start_time, units = "hours")))

Comparing Age and Hours Played

In[7]:
options(repr.plot.width = 4, repr.plot.height = 4)
age_hours_played <- players |>
    ggplot(aes(x = Age, y = played_hours)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.2) +
    labs(x = "Age (years)", y = "Average Played Hours Recorded (hours)", 
           title = "Average Played Hours vs Age") +
    theme(text = element_text(size = 12))
age_hours_played

There appears to be no significant relationship between age and hours_played, although it can be noted that all data points above 50 hours played were all logged by players who were around 15-25 years old.

Comparing Experience and Hours Played

In[8]:
experience_mean <- players |>
    group_by(experience) |>
    summarize(mean_played_hours = mean(played_hours))
options(repr.plot.width = 6, repr.plot.height = 6)
hours_experience <- experience_mean |>
    ggplot(aes(x = experience, y = mean_played_hours, fill = experience)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    labs(x = "Experience Level", y = "Average Played Hours Recorded (hours)", 
           title = "Average Played Hours by Experience Level") +
    theme(text = element_text(size = 12))
hours_experience

Mode: Regular

Players who self-identified as having a "Regular" experience level recorded the highest number of hours spent in-game, followed by "Amateur" players, who logged the second-highest amount of in-game hours.

Methods and Plan

KNN Nearest-Neighbour Regression will be used to predict hours_played based on the predictors "subscribe" and "experience," as they contained the most usable data and showed significant results when compared to hours_played.

Why is this method appropriate?

The dataset is non-linear, and KNN is a flexible algorithm that can capture non-linear relationships between predictor and response variables. Since KNN makes predictions based on the nearest data points, it can effectively handle complex patterns.

Which assumptions are required, if any, to apply the method selected?

  • Feature Scaling: Since KNN relies on distance metrics, features should be normalized or standardized for accurate comparisons.

  • Sufficient Data Density: The dataset should have enough points in each region of the feature space to ensure reliable nearest-neighbor predictions.

  • Choice of k: Selecting an appropriate k value is crucial to balance bias and variance, preventing overfitting or excessive smoothing.

What are the potential limitations or weaknesses of the method selected?

  • Computational Inefficiency: KNN is slow for large datasets since it requires calculating distances for every prediction.

  • Dimensionality: Performance degrades in high-dimensional spaces as distances become less meaningful.

  • Sensitivity to Outliers: Since KNN relies on nearest neighbors, noisy data points or outliers can significantly affect predictions.

  • Speed: The test may be slow because of the large amount of data.

How are you going to compare and select the model?

Evaluate accuracy across different k values (number of neighbors) on the training data and select the k with the highest accuracy. Use cross-validation to ensure the model's performance is not dependent on a single training dataset.

How are you going to process the data to apply the model?

  1. To apply the KNN model, categorical predictors will be converted into numerical values (e.g., experience: beginner = 1, amateur = 2, regular = 3, veteran = 4, pro = 5).

  2. Relevant predictors for played_hours will be selected using visualization techniques. The dataset will be split into 75% training and 25% testing.

  3. Cross-validation will be used to determine the optimal k value. Finally, the model's performance will be evaluated on the testing set.
